WEBVTT

00:01.201 --> 00:04.169
[jazz music]

00:04.203 --> 00:11.010
♪ ♪

00:17.884 --> 00:20.053
[cheers and applause]

00:20.085 --> 00:21.653
- From
the Penn & Teller Theater

00:21.687 --> 00:23.757
at the Rio Hotel in Las Vegas,

00:23.789 --> 00:28.027
here's our host,
Alyson Hannigan!

00:28.060 --> 00:31.097
[cheers and applause]

00:39.805 --> 00:41.274
- Welcome to "Fool Us."

00:41.307 --> 00:44.009
You might think bringing
a magician to Las Vegas

00:44.043 --> 00:45.677
to try and fool Penn and Teller

00:45.712 --> 00:46.880
in their own theater

00:46.912 --> 00:49.615
is like leading a lamb
to the slaughter.

00:49.649 --> 00:52.752
But there's nothing I love
more than the sheepish grin

00:52.786 --> 00:54.387
on a magician's face

00:54.420 --> 00:57.590
when they pull the wool
over Penn and Teller's eyes.

00:57.624 --> 01:00.893
So let's bring out
the "baa-d" boys of magic,

01:00.926 --> 01:02.795
Penn and Teller!

01:02.829 --> 01:05.864
[cheers and applause]

01:17.043 --> 01:19.846
Remember, if a magician fools
Penn and Teller,

01:19.879 --> 01:21.381
they win a slot in their show,

01:21.414 --> 01:22.849
a "Fool Us" trophy,

01:22.882 --> 01:25.385
and international
bragging rights.

01:25.418 --> 01:27.787
Take a look at tonight's
first magician.

01:30.456 --> 01:32.558
- A good magician
is willing to do the work

01:32.591 --> 01:34.394
that no one else
is willing to do.

01:34.426 --> 01:36.829
That's been my philosophy
my entire life.

01:36.862 --> 01:39.865
My first job when I was 13
was in a magic shop.

01:39.899 --> 01:43.503
I took a bus four hours
each day to work for free,

01:43.536 --> 01:46.239
just so I can learn
more about magic.

01:46.271 --> 01:48.108
I wanna be the best
at what I do.

01:48.140 --> 01:51.343
I've even broken
three Guinness World Records,

01:51.377 --> 01:53.947
but I'm still working towards
my ultimate goal in life:

01:53.979 --> 01:56.382
being the world's
most interesting dad.

01:56.415 --> 01:58.418
Tonight, I wanna fool
Penn and Teller.

01:58.450 --> 02:00.686
I've never worked so hard
on anything before.

02:00.719 --> 02:03.856
There's been sleepless nights
in all my efforts.

02:03.890 --> 02:06.659
It's been an obsession
for five freakin' years.

02:06.692 --> 02:10.530
I've done the work,
and now I want that trophy.

02:10.562 --> 02:13.532
[cheers and applause]

02:13.566 --> 02:16.969
- Joined by two random
world-class magicians,

02:17.002 --> 02:21.540
please welcome the fitz-magic
of John Fitzsimmons.

02:21.574 --> 02:23.575
- Thank you.

02:23.610 --> 02:25.677
For the past five years,

02:25.711 --> 02:27.980
my team and I have spent
thousands of dollars

02:28.014 --> 02:30.984
and countless hours
developing a new technology

02:31.016 --> 02:33.186
that allows me
to read your digital aura,

02:33.218 --> 02:34.721
tap into the cloud,

02:34.753 --> 02:37.022
analyze your predictive
thought patterns,

02:37.055 --> 02:40.058
and then "read your minds."

02:40.093 --> 02:43.195
I know the thought of this
technology is terrifying.

02:43.228 --> 02:45.430
So I've actually
cleverly disguised

02:45.465 --> 02:47.332
this bleeding-edge
scientific breakthrough

02:47.366 --> 02:49.668
to look like a card trick.

02:49.701 --> 02:51.371
This is an ordinary
deck of cards.

02:51.403 --> 02:53.406
I'd buy them in bulk.
They're $12.49 a dozen.

02:53.438 --> 02:54.941
I'm up to a pack a day.
It's a bad habit.

02:54.973 --> 02:56.408
I'm trying to cut back.

02:56.442 --> 02:59.579
But I will pull
the seal open right here.

02:59.611 --> 03:01.548
No funny business.

03:01.580 --> 03:04.183
The tab is taped.

03:04.217 --> 03:06.752
Break that open.

03:07.520 --> 03:10.056
We'll get rid of the little
advertising cards

03:10.088 --> 03:15.360
and the jokers,
leaving us with our 52 friends.

03:15.395 --> 03:17.030
Okay. I'm gonna give 'em
a quick mix.

03:17.062 --> 03:19.498
[soft music]

03:19.532 --> 03:21.234
And Alyson,
if you would help me first,

03:21.266 --> 03:23.502
go ahead and take the cards.

03:23.536 --> 03:25.038
Go through the deck.
Find any card you like.

03:25.070 --> 03:27.539
It could be a favorite card.
It could be a random card.

03:27.574 --> 03:29.074
It could be
your least favorite card.

03:29.108 --> 03:31.243
I mean, who likes the eight
of diamonds anyway, right?

03:31.276 --> 03:33.812
- [gasps]
- Just take any card you like,

03:33.846 --> 03:35.814
pull it out of the deck,
and hang onto it

03:35.848 --> 03:38.550
in case we need it
as evidence later.

03:38.585 --> 03:40.586
All right. In fact,
I'll take the cards back,

03:40.620 --> 03:42.055
and if you would
just hold that card

03:42.087 --> 03:44.022
between your hands
like--that was perfect too.

03:44.057 --> 03:45.991
Just so I can't see
the card at all.

03:46.025 --> 03:48.493
And Penn, I'm gonna have you
take the deck and go ahead

03:48.527 --> 03:50.530
and remove any card you like,
do the same thing.

03:50.562 --> 03:52.497
It could be your favorite card,
your least favorite card.

03:52.531 --> 03:54.199
The choice is yours.

03:54.234 --> 03:56.336
I'll look over here at Alyson.
Hi.

03:56.368 --> 03:57.870
And then hand the deck
to Teller.

03:57.903 --> 04:00.340
And Teller, I'm guessing
you know what to do by now.

04:00.372 --> 04:03.443
Go ahead and remove
any card you like.

04:03.475 --> 04:04.443
All right.

04:04.477 --> 04:05.944
And I will take the cards back,

04:05.979 --> 04:08.681
and now the fun can begin.

04:08.715 --> 04:11.550
Some assembly required.

04:11.584 --> 04:14.721
♪ ♪

04:14.753 --> 04:16.656
Let's see here.

04:16.689 --> 04:20.293
[playful music]

04:20.326 --> 04:22.228
This is the

04:22.262 --> 04:26.165
Serious Thought Uploading
Psychic Infused Dynamic Hat,

04:26.199 --> 04:28.533
or as my wife
likes to call it...

04:28.567 --> 04:30.836
the S.T.U.P.I.D. hat.
[laughter]

04:30.870 --> 04:32.872
I'm gonna put it on
and buckle up

04:32.904 --> 04:34.374
in case it's a bumpy ride.

04:34.406 --> 04:38.377
♪ ♪

04:38.411 --> 04:40.512
All right, now, this hat--
I know, right?

04:40.545 --> 04:43.483
This hat is packed full
of the latest technology.

04:43.516 --> 04:45.651
It's got machine learning,
artificial intelligence,

04:45.685 --> 04:48.855
a 2.4 gigahertz
wireless data connection.

04:48.887 --> 04:51.356
It's got buttons, switches,
and a knob.

04:51.391 --> 04:53.692
Not only that,
but it's got over 100

04:53.725 --> 04:55.161
light emitting diodes.

04:55.194 --> 04:56.663
In the right conditions,

04:56.696 --> 04:58.997
you can see this thing
from space.

04:59.031 --> 05:00.165
[electronic warbling]

05:00.199 --> 05:01.934
Ooh!
- Aww.

05:01.968 --> 05:04.103
- I know, right?
I'm excited too.

05:04.137 --> 05:06.773
Now, what I want you to do
is concentrate on your cards.

05:06.805 --> 05:09.341
In a moment, I'm gonna try
to read your digital aura

05:09.375 --> 05:11.711
and then tell you exactly
what cards you've chosen.

05:11.744 --> 05:13.278
Are you ready?

05:13.312 --> 05:16.548
Alyson, I want you to think
of the color of your card.

05:16.581 --> 05:19.384
Just send it to me.
Okay. Good. Good.

05:19.418 --> 05:20.653
I'm getting
a little interference today.

05:20.687 --> 05:22.154
I don't know what it is.

05:22.187 --> 05:24.956
Go ahead and send me the color
of your cards, gentlemen.

05:24.990 --> 05:28.161
Let's see. All right.

05:28.194 --> 05:30.196
Now, Alyson, I want you
to send me your suit.

05:30.228 --> 05:33.231
Think of your suit.
Just concentrate on your suit.

05:33.266 --> 05:36.502
All right, gentlemen,
concentrate on your suits.

05:36.536 --> 05:39.971
Concentrate.
Not pin-striped suits, guys.

05:40.005 --> 05:42.507
Your playing card suits.
Okay. Thank you.

05:42.542 --> 05:43.709
All right.

05:43.742 --> 05:47.146
Now, Alyson,
think of your value.

05:47.180 --> 05:49.415
Perfect.

05:49.449 --> 05:52.018
And then gentlemen,
think of the value.

05:52.050 --> 05:53.853
All right. Now, in a moment,

05:53.886 --> 05:56.488
I'm going to reveal the cards.

05:56.521 --> 05:59.024
Once I reveal the cards,
if you could just clap,

05:59.057 --> 06:01.160
letting everybody here know

06:01.194 --> 06:02.495
that I've actually
named your cards.

06:02.528 --> 06:05.331
Are you ready for this?
All right.

06:05.365 --> 06:08.334
[dramatic music]

06:08.367 --> 06:10.769
♪ ♪

06:10.802 --> 06:12.038
I'm getting the ace of diamonds

06:12.071 --> 06:13.939
and the six of diamonds.

06:13.973 --> 06:15.440
If I've got your card,

06:15.475 --> 06:18.144
just show it to the audience
or show it here.

06:18.177 --> 06:20.545
[applause]

06:20.579 --> 06:22.180
Okay. That's two cards.
I didn't get all three.

06:22.214 --> 06:23.649
I'm sorry.
It's that interference.

06:23.682 --> 06:24.516
I'm gonna need my antenna.

06:24.550 --> 06:25.951
[whirring]

06:25.985 --> 06:28.454
- Aww. [laughs]

06:28.487 --> 06:29.988
- All right, Penn.
You ready to do this?

06:30.021 --> 06:31.490
- I am.
- Okay.

06:31.524 --> 06:32.891
That's not bad, though.
Two out of three is not bad.

06:32.925 --> 06:34.793
Let's go for all three.

06:34.826 --> 06:36.194
♪ ♪

06:36.228 --> 06:38.965
Send me the color of your card.

06:38.997 --> 06:41.567
I'm getting a red card,
a heart.

06:41.600 --> 06:43.502
I want you really
to shout it out with your mind.

06:43.536 --> 06:45.071
Just send it to me.
Are you ready?

06:45.103 --> 06:48.740
On the count of three.
Here we go. One, two, three.

06:48.774 --> 06:50.475
[electricity zapping]

06:50.509 --> 06:52.245
♪ ♪

06:52.278 --> 06:53.846
It's clearly a red card.
It's a heart.

06:53.879 --> 06:55.415
The eight of hearts.

06:55.447 --> 06:56.682
Go ahead and show everybody.

06:56.716 --> 06:59.252
The eight of hearts,
the magic of technology.

06:59.284 --> 07:00.653
I'm John Fitzsimmons.

07:00.685 --> 07:02.788
Thank you very much, gentlemen.

07:02.822 --> 07:05.324
- John Fitzsimmons!

07:05.358 --> 07:07.125
- Well, thank you very much.

07:07.160 --> 07:08.360
[cheers and applause]

07:08.394 --> 07:11.163
- That was so good.

07:11.197 --> 07:12.598
That was incredible.

07:12.632 --> 07:13.865
- I've literally spent
five years

07:13.899 --> 07:15.535
developing that trick
just to be here tonight.

07:15.567 --> 07:17.637
- Well, you definitely
win the award

07:17.670 --> 07:19.672
for the silliest hat
we've ever had on the show.

07:19.704 --> 07:21.641
- Well, thank you very much.
That's an honor right there.

07:21.673 --> 07:23.309
- So are you
a full-time magician?

07:23.341 --> 07:24.843
- I'm a stay-at-home dad
during the week,

07:24.877 --> 07:26.879
and then I get to do magic
on the nights and weekends.

07:26.913 --> 07:28.447
- Aww.

07:28.480 --> 07:30.348
- And do fun adventures
like this as well.

07:30.382 --> 07:32.851
Currently, I'm training
for the world's fastest

07:32.884 --> 07:35.153
straitjacket escape
from a regulation straitjacket

07:35.187 --> 07:36.889
while riding a unicycle.

07:36.923 --> 07:39.192
- Is there a lot
of competition in that field?

07:39.225 --> 07:40.526
- So far,
no one has the record.

07:40.560 --> 07:43.028
- I just--I'm picturing
your neighborhood,

07:43.062 --> 07:44.230
and, like, the neighbors
are like,

07:44.262 --> 07:45.865
"Oh, there he goes again."
- Every day.

07:45.898 --> 07:47.233
Every day. I'm on it--

07:47.266 --> 07:49.168
- Do your kids
inspire new tricks?

07:49.201 --> 07:51.370
- Absolutely. Yeah.
All the time.

07:51.403 --> 07:53.372
In fact, I still use
my seven-year-old's diaper

07:53.406 --> 07:54.874
in my kid show to this day,

07:54.906 --> 07:56.843
and yeah, it's--
- Ew.

07:56.875 --> 07:58.845
- Well, it's not a used
diaper; it's a clean one.

07:58.877 --> 08:00.146
But it gets a laugh every time.

08:00.178 --> 08:02.180
- Okay, good. Okay, John.

08:02.214 --> 08:03.850
I think they've
had plenty of time

08:03.882 --> 08:05.685
to reverse engineer this trick.

08:05.718 --> 08:06.819
Don't you?
- I hope not.

08:06.853 --> 08:09.689
[both laughing]

08:09.721 --> 08:12.358
- Oh, John,
you--you wily bastard.

08:12.391 --> 08:17.663
I think that you kind of
told us how it was done

08:17.697 --> 08:19.165
while you were doing it.

08:19.197 --> 08:21.766
I mean, you said
it was technology.

08:21.800 --> 08:23.134
You lied about one thing.

08:23.168 --> 08:25.036
It's not stupid technology.

08:25.071 --> 08:27.339
It's wicked smart technology.

08:27.372 --> 08:29.975
You had that stupid helmet
with the switches

08:30.009 --> 08:32.711
and all that stuff going on
and just said,

08:32.745 --> 08:34.947
"Oh, this helmet
is just make-believe."

08:34.980 --> 08:37.283
The helmet is actually doing
part of the trick.

08:37.316 --> 08:40.286
You actually were telling us
what you were doing.

08:40.318 --> 08:43.956
And, you know, you always try
to claim for creativity

08:43.990 --> 08:47.058
to think outside the box,
but a lot of time,

08:47.092 --> 08:50.296
the really creative people
think inside the box.

08:50.328 --> 08:52.331
And you were doing that,
thinking inside the box

08:52.365 --> 08:55.735
in terms of this is what
a good card trick should be.

08:55.768 --> 08:57.036
The work you do,

08:57.068 --> 09:00.005
wicked complicated,
wicked technological,

09:00.038 --> 09:01.606
and wicked tied to that helmet

09:01.640 --> 09:03.643
with all its switches
and knobs and so on.

09:03.676 --> 09:05.610
So I think we have something.

09:05.644 --> 09:07.312
I don't know.
Surprise me.

09:07.346 --> 09:09.981
- All right.
That was all gibberish to me.

09:10.015 --> 09:11.583
John, do they know
how you did your trick?

09:11.616 --> 09:13.852
- I think they do.
I think they do.

09:13.885 --> 09:15.321
These guys are geniuses.
- [laughs]

09:15.354 --> 09:16.154
- Thank you so much
for having me.

09:16.187 --> 09:17.289
- Well, thank you.
It was great.

09:17.322 --> 09:18.423
- This is truly a dream
come true.

09:18.456 --> 09:20.025
- Oh, you were amazing.

09:20.058 --> 09:22.427
Thank you, John Fitzsimmons.
- Thank you.

09:22.461 --> 09:23.596
Thank you.

09:23.629 --> 09:26.231
[cheers and applause]

09:27.799 --> 09:28.833
- Stick around.

09:28.868 --> 09:31.037
More "Fool Us" coming up
after the break.

09:31.070 --> 09:34.139
[cheers and applause]

09:38.911 --> 09:41.113
[jazz music]

09:41.147 --> 09:43.950
[cheers and applause]

09:43.982 --> 09:45.451
- Welcome back to "Fool Us,"

09:45.484 --> 09:48.486
where playing cards
are never used for blackjack.

09:48.520 --> 09:50.956
Let's see if a "Fool Us" trophy
is in the cards

09:50.990 --> 09:52.191
for our next magician.

09:54.860 --> 09:57.296
- When my son Matthew
was one year old,

09:57.330 --> 09:59.398
he was diagnosed
with type 1 diabetes,

09:59.432 --> 10:02.033
and that opens up your eyes
quite a bit.

10:02.067 --> 10:04.003
Ten years later,
he's doing great,

10:04.035 --> 10:05.638
but I still try
to use my magic

10:05.671 --> 10:07.673
to help raise money
and spread awareness

10:07.706 --> 10:10.509
of type 1 diabetes
through different foundations.

10:10.543 --> 10:12.144
- Oh, my God!

10:12.177 --> 10:14.513
- People ask me
if I can support

10:14.547 --> 10:17.216
a family of four
on a magician's salary.

10:17.249 --> 10:19.184
Well, they don't
say it like that.

10:19.217 --> 10:21.187
They say,
"Oh, you're a magician.

10:21.220 --> 10:22.822
Do you have a real job?"

10:22.855 --> 10:23.822
- Oh, my God.

10:23.855 --> 10:25.191
- And I do have a real job.

10:25.224 --> 10:26.591
I'm in show business.

10:26.625 --> 10:27.592
- Come on!

10:27.626 --> 10:29.227
- Magic is the show,

10:29.260 --> 10:31.831
and marketing is my business.

10:31.864 --> 10:34.265
Magic and marketing
have a lot in common.

10:34.299 --> 10:36.601
In both cases,
I'm using psychology

10:36.635 --> 10:39.205
to try to get people
to do what I want.

10:39.238 --> 10:40.740
Tonight, I'm gonna be using

10:40.773 --> 10:43.609
a very powerful
psychological technique.

10:43.643 --> 10:45.010
[bell dings]

10:45.043 --> 10:47.879
Let's see if it works
on Penn and Teller.

10:47.913 --> 10:50.548
[cheers and applause]

10:50.582 --> 10:55.120
- Joined by Penn and Teller,
here's David Corsaro.

10:55.153 --> 10:56.389
[cheers and applause]

10:56.422 --> 10:57.923
- Thank you.

10:57.956 --> 10:59.290
You know, as a magician,

10:59.325 --> 11:01.826
I'm constantly looking
for new ways to influence

11:01.860 --> 11:03.863
what people say
and what they do.

11:03.895 --> 11:06.499
And recently,
my research has led me to--

11:06.532 --> 11:08.900
you guessed it--
Ivan Pavlov.

11:08.933 --> 11:10.001
- [laughs]

11:10.035 --> 11:11.236
- Now, hopefully
for some of you,

11:11.269 --> 11:13.239
that name rings a bell.

11:13.272 --> 11:15.341
[laughter]
Let me explain.

11:15.374 --> 11:16.642
If you believe the saying

11:16.676 --> 11:18.744
that you can't teach
an old dog new tricks,

11:18.778 --> 11:20.546
then Ivan Pavlov

11:20.578 --> 11:22.748
was one of the greatest
magic teachers of all time,

11:22.782 --> 11:25.817
because he discovered that you
could train a dog to salivate

11:25.850 --> 11:27.153
just by ringing a bell.

11:27.186 --> 11:28.386
That's right.

11:28.421 --> 11:29.654
Every time he rang a bell...

11:29.688 --> 11:32.224
[bell rings]
His dog drooled.

11:32.258 --> 11:34.159
So tonight,
I'm gonna to try to apply

11:34.192 --> 11:39.097
that same scientific technique
to the Great Danes of magic,

11:39.130 --> 11:42.368
Penn and Teller,
but not to make you drool.

11:42.400 --> 11:44.703
But hopefully
to make you fooled.

11:44.736 --> 11:45.705
- Hmm.

11:45.738 --> 11:47.373
- Let me explain.

11:47.405 --> 11:49.174
As part of my journey
to try to fool...

11:49.207 --> 11:50.042
[bell rings]
Penn and Teller,

11:50.076 --> 11:51.443
I decided to study

11:51.476 --> 11:52.544
all of the foolers...
[bell rings]

11:52.577 --> 11:54.212
From the past and see

11:54.245 --> 11:56.215
if there was a common
denominator of things

11:56.248 --> 11:57.950
that successfully fooled...

11:57.982 --> 11:59.051
[bell rings]
Penn and Teller

11:59.085 --> 12:00.385
and things
that didn't fool...

12:00.418 --> 12:01.486
[bell rings]
Them.

12:01.519 --> 12:03.221
I even went back and watched

12:03.254 --> 12:05.557
all of the past episodes
of "Fool"...

12:05.591 --> 12:06.792
[bell rings]
"Us"

12:06.826 --> 12:09.562
and made a list
of the words and phrases

12:09.595 --> 12:13.466
that Penn had used most often
every time he was describing

12:13.499 --> 12:15.067
a successful a fooler.

12:15.100 --> 12:16.335
[bell rings]
Now, you can see the words

12:16.368 --> 12:18.203
come in all different shapes
and sizes.

12:18.236 --> 12:20.572
Good, creative, confident,
comfortable, smart,

12:20.605 --> 12:24.844
strong, powerful, cool,
clever, unique, exciting.

12:24.876 --> 12:26.644
I even put the word
that Teller used most often.

12:26.678 --> 12:28.346
- Mm.
- [laughs]

12:28.379 --> 12:29.548
