[laughter]

28:54.732 --> 28:58.068
After all, what makes
a superhero a superhero?

28:58.103 --> 29:00.404
Magic powers.

29:00.438 --> 29:01.772
Penn, before the show,
I asked you to sign

29:01.806 --> 29:03.508
a $100 bill
and give it to Alyson.

29:03.540 --> 29:05.477
Did you do that?
- Yes, I did.

29:05.509 --> 29:07.746
- Alyson, please bring me
Penn's signed bill.

29:07.778 --> 29:09.314
[cheers and applause]

29:09.346 --> 29:11.849
Now, before you hand it to me,
show the camera,

29:11.883 --> 29:13.351
'cause I want everyone to know

29:13.384 --> 29:15.153
that there's no
funny business going on

29:15.185 --> 29:17.454
and that my superpowers
are genuine.

29:17.489 --> 29:19.156
[laughter]

29:19.190 --> 29:21.960
Now, every superhero
has to have a super villain,

29:21.992 --> 29:26.029
so I'd like you all
to meet...The Shredder.

29:26.064 --> 29:28.599
[laughter]
- Aww.

29:28.633 --> 29:31.435
- To prove to you
that he's real,

29:31.469 --> 29:33.471
he has shredded abs.

29:33.505 --> 29:34.471
[whirring]

29:34.506 --> 29:37.142
[laughter]

29:37.174 --> 29:38.942
Of course,
every great superhero

29:38.977 --> 29:41.445
must also have
a trusty sidekick.

29:41.479 --> 29:42.947
So, Alyson, would you please
be my sidekick?

29:42.980 --> 29:44.281
- Sure.

29:44.315 --> 29:45.316
- Obviously, you need
a costume.

29:45.349 --> 29:48.318
- Oh, perfect.
[laughter]

29:48.353 --> 29:50.488
- Now, in addition to Penn's
one of a kind signed bill,

29:50.521 --> 29:53.157
I also have three fake bills.

29:53.191 --> 29:55.460
And to prove they're
100% real fakes,

29:55.492 --> 29:58.296
they have the word fake
written on them.

29:58.328 --> 30:00.030
Alyson, what I'd like you to do

30:00.064 --> 30:02.232
is to take these fake bills

30:02.267 --> 30:06.637
and put 'em in the envelopes
and seal them up.

30:06.671 --> 30:08.038
- Okay, I'm gonna have
to do that without my costume.

30:08.071 --> 30:09.039
- That's fine.
That's--

30:09.073 --> 30:10.508
- Thank you.

30:10.541 --> 30:14.711
- And I will do the same thing
to Penn's bill here.

30:14.746 --> 30:17.749
[suspenseful music]

30:17.781 --> 30:21.419
So we'll have three bills
that are fake

30:21.451 --> 30:23.855
and one bill signed by Penn.

30:23.887 --> 30:25.690
- All right, two.

30:25.722 --> 30:26.990
- Now, Alyson, what I'd like
you to do is take those

30:27.025 --> 30:28.492
and mix 'em up behind your back

30:28.526 --> 30:29.827
so that neither of us know

30:29.861 --> 30:32.864
which envelope has Penn's bill.

30:32.896 --> 30:33.932
- Behind my back.
- Yes.

30:33.964 --> 30:35.432
- Easier said than done.

30:35.465 --> 30:37.101
- Why am I doing all this?
You may ask.

30:37.134 --> 30:39.037
Well, that's because
I'm not really a superhero

30:39.069 --> 30:44.174
unless I save someone,
or in this case, something.

30:44.209 --> 30:45.676
Penn's $100 bill.

30:45.710 --> 30:47.111
♪ ♪

30:47.144 --> 30:49.513
- Okay.
- All right.

30:49.547 --> 30:51.615
Alyson, do you see any special
markings on the envelopes?

30:51.648 --> 30:53.183
♪ ♪

30:53.218 --> 30:54.352
- No.
- Do they feel

30:54.384 --> 30:56.253
and look identical
to the naked eye?

30:56.287 --> 30:57.521
- Yeah.

30:57.555 --> 30:59.590
- Well, that's
because they are.

30:59.624 --> 31:01.058
Ordinary vision can't
pick out the real bill

31:01.092 --> 31:02.660
from the fake ones.

31:02.693 --> 31:07.164
To do that, you need only
what I have, X-ray vision.

31:07.198 --> 31:08.866
And to make this
truly convincing,

31:08.900 --> 31:11.236
I'm gonna put on
my own superhero costume.

31:11.269 --> 31:12.871
[dramatic music]

31:12.903 --> 31:15.205
Now, my X-ray vision
can see through the envelopes,

31:15.240 --> 31:16.907
but to make this
even more amazing,

31:16.941 --> 31:19.743
I'll see through
this blindfold as well.

31:19.777 --> 31:22.046
Alyson, what I'd like you to do
is pick up two envelopes,

31:22.079 --> 31:24.315
one in each hand,
any two you want.

31:24.348 --> 31:26.851
Let me know
when you've done that.

31:26.884 --> 31:28.152
- Okay. I've done it.

31:28.185 --> 31:29.253
- All right.

31:29.287 --> 31:32.323
[lively theme music]

31:32.356 --> 31:33.825
Give me the one
in your left hand.

31:33.857 --> 31:34.826
- [laughs]

31:34.858 --> 31:37.228
[laughter]

31:37.261 --> 31:41.365
And our Shredder
does his worst.

31:41.398 --> 31:42.599
Alyson, what I'd like you to do

31:42.634 --> 31:44.669
is put one envelope
in each hand again.

31:44.701 --> 31:46.537
♪ ♪

31:46.570 --> 31:47.672
- Okay.

31:47.704 --> 31:50.441
♪ ♪

31:50.474 --> 31:53.677
- My Bentley vision says
the one in your right hand.

31:53.711 --> 31:56.413
♪ ♪

31:56.447 --> 31:59.784
And another bites the dust.

31:59.817 --> 32:02.353
Now, with only two
envelopes remaining,

32:02.386 --> 32:05.022
it's time to use another
one of my superpowers.

32:05.056 --> 32:07.291
Mind control.

32:07.325 --> 32:08.459
Give me the last two envelopes.

32:08.492 --> 32:11.395
One in each hand.
Look me in the eyes.

32:11.429 --> 32:14.164
♪ ♪

32:14.198 --> 32:15.666
I've now taken over
your consciousness.

32:15.700 --> 32:17.134
- Oh, dear.
[laughter]

32:17.167 --> 32:18.303
- You will pick one envelope.

32:18.336 --> 32:20.371
The one I'm
controlling you to pick,

32:20.404 --> 32:23.007
and it will go into
the belly of the shredder.

32:23.040 --> 32:24.075
♪ ♪

32:24.107 --> 32:26.176
Which envelope?

32:26.210 --> 32:27.979
- That one.
- That one? All right.

32:28.011 --> 32:30.748
♪ ♪

32:30.781 --> 32:34.352
And away it goes.

32:34.384 --> 32:36.386
Now, if our mind meld worked,

32:36.421 --> 32:38.855
then Penn's bill
is inside this envelope,

32:38.890 --> 32:40.258
we have saved the day,

32:40.290 --> 32:43.827
and the Earth will continue
its path around the sun!

32:43.861 --> 32:46.029
Take the bill, show it to Penn.

32:46.064 --> 32:48.165
♪ ♪

32:48.199 --> 32:50.401
Penn, is that your signature?

32:50.434 --> 32:51.435
- Yes.

32:51.469 --> 32:53.104
- Well, then I'm Bentley Burns,

32:53.136 --> 32:55.506
and my work here is done.

32:55.539 --> 32:56.907
[cheers and applause]

32:56.941 --> 33:00.877
- Bentley Burns!

33:00.912 --> 33:02.279
Well, that was fun.

33:02.313 --> 33:04.214
- Thank you.
- You're like a little kid.

33:04.248 --> 33:06.784
- I am always a little kid,
at heart, at heart.

33:06.817 --> 33:09.354
- Yeah.
So what kind of kid were you?

33:09.386 --> 33:11.321
- I was kind of a class clown.
Always had fun,

33:11.355 --> 33:13.324
messing around,
doing impressions.

33:13.357 --> 33:16.160
Always performing.
I was a theater kid.

33:16.193 --> 33:17.828
- Did you get in trouble
at school?

33:17.862 --> 33:19.364
- If my mom's watching?

33:19.396 --> 33:22.799
No, but in reality sometimes,
you know, a little bit.

33:22.834 --> 33:24.402
- Your teachers
are like, "Yes."

33:24.434 --> 33:26.703
- Yes. I remember,
like I said, as a kid,

33:26.738 --> 33:29.673
I would kind of prank people
with my magic at school

33:29.707 --> 33:31.976
and that's where I kind of
got in trouble a little bit.

33:32.009 --> 33:33.978
[laughter]

33:34.011 --> 33:35.246
- All right, Bentley, let's see

33:35.278 --> 33:36.814
if you can take home
a trophy to Tupelo.

33:36.847 --> 33:38.415
- I would love to.

33:38.449 --> 33:41.251
- Nice robot.
Nicely shredded, the eyes.

33:41.285 --> 33:42.185
It's very, very good.
- Thank you.

33:42.220 --> 33:44.255
- I like using a robot in this.

33:44.288 --> 33:48.192
That's a really good thing.
I like the superhero theme.

33:48.226 --> 33:49.727
- Thank you.
- Like your whole vibe.

33:49.760 --> 33:50.862
- Oh, wow. Thank you.
- Very good. Very funny.

33:50.894 --> 33:52.230
Very nice.

33:52.262 --> 33:54.598
And, you know,
you also gave away

33:54.632 --> 33:57.167
one of the biggest secrets
of all of magic,

33:57.201 --> 33:59.569
which I hope
everybody's okay with,

33:59.604 --> 34:02.440
and that is that magicians
do have superpowers.

34:02.472 --> 34:03.840
- Oh, that's true. Yes.

34:03.875 --> 34:05.542
- You have your X-ray vision,
your mind control,

34:05.576 --> 34:06.978
but we have a superpower too.

34:07.010 --> 34:08.112
You had one moment in there

34:08.146 --> 34:10.313
that tipped off
our spidey sense.

34:10.347 --> 34:11.382
- Uh-oh.

34:11.416 --> 34:12.884
- Got that tingling
and gave us

34:12.916 --> 34:14.885
a pretty good idea
of how you did it,

34:14.918 --> 34:18.856
but your version of kind
of a different bank night

34:18.889 --> 34:20.690
or different
also Russian roulette,

34:20.724 --> 34:22.126
also the same plot,

34:22.159 --> 34:24.461
very nice way putting
the whole superhero thing.

34:24.494 --> 34:26.864
And we liked it very much,
but we think we snuck in

34:26.898 --> 34:28.365
a thing or two of the things

34:28.398 --> 34:30.201
that you might have
gotten there that shows

34:30.233 --> 34:32.369
that we have a pretty
good idea how you did it.

34:32.402 --> 34:33.971
- I think my spidey sense
is tingling there,

34:34.005 --> 34:36.139
too, that they know exactly.

34:36.173 --> 34:37.340
So thank you
for having me, though.

34:37.375 --> 34:38.076
- Nicely done, Bentley.
- Thank you.

34:38.108 --> 34:39.976
- Thank you, Bentley Burns!

34:40.010 --> 34:41.179
- Thank you.

34:41.211 --> 34:42.746
[cheers and applause]

34:42.780 --> 34:43.981
- Don't go anywhere.

34:44.014 --> 34:46.184
Penn and Teller
take the stage next,

34:46.217 --> 34:48.920
and they've got something
really special to show you.

34:48.952 --> 34:50.188
We'll be right back.

34:50.221 --> 34:53.023
[cheers and applause]

34:57.961 --> 35:00.097
[jazz music]

35:00.130 --> 35:02.632
[cheers and applause]

35:02.666 --> 35:04.202
- Welcome back.

35:04.235 --> 35:06.436
This next trick
currently is the finale

35:06.471 --> 35:09.005
of Penn and Teller's
live Las Vegas show,

35:09.039 --> 35:11.708
and tonight it's the finale
of our show.

35:11.742 --> 35:13.811
Here are
the legends themselves,

35:13.844 --> 35:16.047
Penn and Teller!

35:16.079 --> 35:19.449
[cheers and applause]

35:19.483 --> 35:22.686
- Everything that Teller and I
do in our shows

35:22.719 --> 35:24.121
comes from a love that we share

35:24.155 --> 35:27.657
of the American sideshow,
the freak show.

35:27.692 --> 35:30.061
[soft music]

35:30.094 --> 35:33.664
When I was a child,
for just 75 cents,

35:33.697 --> 35:37.367
you could see ten different
freaks under one tent.

35:37.400 --> 35:39.003
And I loved them all,

35:39.036 --> 35:41.405
but I especially loved
the self-made freaks.

35:41.438 --> 35:45.143
The fire eater,
the sword swallower.

35:45.175 --> 35:47.878
And my friends would go
with me to the show.

35:47.911 --> 35:49.713
My friends were different.

35:49.746 --> 35:53.016
They did the whole show with
some sort of weird challenge

35:53.050 --> 35:57.021
and all through this
fire eater's perfect act,

35:57.054 --> 35:58.222
my friends would be talking,

35:58.255 --> 35:59.690
and they'd
be saying stuff like,

35:59.724 --> 36:01.692
"Oh, I know
how he does that, Penn.

36:01.726 --> 36:04.528
He just coats his mouth
with something."

36:04.561 --> 36:06.164
They'd try to convince me
there was some sort

36:06.197 --> 36:08.865
of something
you could smear in your mouth

36:08.900 --> 36:11.135
and go suck on a soldering iron

36:11.168 --> 36:13.036
and it wasn't gonna hurt you.

36:13.070 --> 36:14.304
And it's not just children.

36:14.338 --> 36:17.175
It's also adults.
And it's usually a man.

36:17.208 --> 36:20.010
And it's most often a man
with some woman

36:20.043 --> 36:21.445
he's trying desperately

36:21.478 --> 36:24.014
and often pathetically
to impress.

36:24.047 --> 36:27.284
And one of these guys who
thinks it's part of being cool

36:27.318 --> 36:29.219
to pretend to know everything,
so he'll be going like,

36:29.253 --> 36:31.355
"Oh, don't worry
about him, honey.

36:31.389 --> 36:33.690
He's just using cold fire."

36:33.724 --> 36:36.494
[laughter]

36:36.527 --> 36:39.197
Well, all these years
have passed,

36:39.230 --> 36:43.134
and I turned out
to be a fire eater.

36:43.166 --> 36:44.735
And the ironic thing
I found out

36:44.768 --> 36:46.836
is there's no trick,
not to this.

36:46.871 --> 36:48.139
To everything else we do,
there's a trick.

36:48.172 --> 36:50.740
It's lie, cheat,
swindle, rip off.

36:50.775 --> 36:53.811
That is what we do.

36:53.844 --> 36:57.347
But not fire eating.
Fire eating's a stunt.

36:57.380 --> 37:00.351
And there's no such thing
as cold fire.

37:00.384 --> 37:02.286
If you still believe
there is such a thing,

37:02.320 --> 37:05.356
you think I might be using it,
wait till I get it lit.

37:05.389 --> 37:06.690
I'll stick it in your eye.

37:06.724 --> 37:08.992
Get empirical real fast.

37:09.025 --> 37:11.329
Teller's coming out here
with a fireproof

37:11.362 --> 37:14.297
camping fuel container,
and it is lighter fluid

37:14.331 --> 37:16.032
that he's dipping
the torches in.

37:16.067 --> 37:20.972
The torches are cotton rope
wrapped around a metal rod

37:21.005 --> 37:23.039
screwed into a wooden handle.

37:23.074 --> 37:24.275
It's not the cotton that burns.

37:24.307 --> 37:26.177
It's the fuel that burns.

37:26.210 --> 37:28.378
And the way fire eating works
is this.

37:28.411 --> 37:30.681
You get a lot of moisture
throughout your mouth

37:30.715 --> 37:33.451
and all that moisture
has got to evaporate

37:33.483 --> 37:34.851
from any given part
of your mouth

37:34.885 --> 37:36.454
before that part will burn.

37:36.487 --> 37:39.155
So you learn how to handle
the burning vapors.

37:39.190 --> 37:40.324
Then you gotta try
to make it look good.

37:40.358 --> 37:43.693
Now, if you get a lot
of saliva in your mouth,

37:43.728 --> 37:47.331
and that's at least where
I try to keep most of mine,

37:47.364 --> 37:49.132
you can rub your lips
right on the cotton

37:49.166 --> 37:50.568
and pull that vapor off.

37:50.601 --> 37:52.503
The vapor's still burning,

37:52.536 --> 37:53.704
but if you breathe in
just a little bit,

37:53.737 --> 37:56.373
the audience can't see it.

37:56.407 --> 37:59.076
So you get
a beautiful surprise there.

37:59.110 --> 38:00.277
Then you just wait
till the time is right

38:00.311 --> 38:04.481
and then just let it flow
like it was magic smoke.

38:04.514 --> 38:07.684
If you wanna put the fire out,
there's a move for that too.

38:07.717 --> 38:11.155
And it's the move that
gives it the name fire eating.

38:11.188 --> 38:13.291
Now, you're not actually
eating the flame,

38:13.324 --> 38:16.427
but I guess they figure
that oral fire extinguishing

38:16.460 --> 38:18.161
didn't sound that butch.

38:18.195 --> 38:19.864
When you feel your mouth
drying out,

38:19.896 --> 38:21.632
you close your lips tightly.

38:21.666 --> 38:25.302
That cuts out most of
the oxygen and fire goes out.

38:25.335 --> 38:27.438
Now, when I
was being taught this,

38:27.471 --> 38:29.106
I got burned
every time I tried it,

38:29.139 --> 38:30.875
and I still
get burned occasionally.

38:30.907 --> 38:32.976
But the burns you get
from fire eating

38:33.010 --> 38:36.146
are for the most part
extremely minor.

38:36.179 --> 38:37.380
They're the kind of burns
you get, you know,

38:37.414 --> 38:39.516
when you eat a pizza too fast,

38:39.550 --> 38:42.619
the cheese will snag,
or you gulp some hot coffee.

38:42.652 --> 38:45.556
And I'm not talking
mind over matter jive.

38:45.588 --> 38:47.123
There's no such thing.

38:47.157 --> 38:48.958
It just hurts like holy hell,

38:48.992 --> 38:51.695
but it's not dangerous.

38:51.728 --> 38:53.230
The dangerous things

38:53.264 --> 38:55.333
that laypeople
hardly ever think about.

38:55.365 --> 38:57.168
And that is every time
you do this act,

38:57.201 --> 39:00.603
no matter how carefully
or how well,

39:00.637 --> 39:02.773
you swallow about a teaspoon
of the lighter fluid.

39:02.806 --> 39:04.342
And that stuff is poisonous.

39:04.375 --> 39:06.010
That's why they go
to the extra trouble

39:06.043 --> 39:08.478
to write "harmful or fatal
if swallowed"

39:08.512 --> 39:10.246
right there on the can.

39:10.280 --> 39:13.583
And the effect is
to a certain degree cumulative.

39:13.617 --> 39:16.420
Now, I say a certain degree.
I do four shows a week.

39:16.454 --> 39:19.356
I'm a big guy,
that doesn't affect me,

39:19.389 --> 39:23.994
but carnival workers
in real showbiz,

39:24.027 --> 39:26.463
they'll do
up to 30 shows a day.

39:26.496 --> 39:28.798
In as little
as two or three years,

39:28.833 --> 39:30.034
that stuff will build up
in their liver

39:30.067 --> 39:31.534
and they'll get sick enough

39:31.568 --> 39:32.936
they have to take time off

39:32.969 --> 39:34.938
and do another line of work
in the carnival,

39:34.972 --> 39:39.376
while that liver regenerates,
which thankfully it will do.

39:39.409 --> 39:42.112
Now, we take all this time

39:42.146 --> 39:45.648
to explain all of this to you
in such detail,

39:45.682 --> 39:48.552
because we think
it's more fascinating

39:48.585 --> 39:51.956
to think of someone
poisoning themselves to death

39:51.989 --> 39:55.358
slowly on stage
than merely burning themselves.

39:55.393 --> 39:58.461
And after all, we're here
to entertain you.

39:58.496 --> 40:01.030
[laughter]

40:01.065 --> 40:04.635
We really tell you this
'cause we're doing this stuff.

40:04.668 --> 40:09.072
We don't want you to be
thinking about how we did it.

40:09.106 --> 40:10.974
We want you to be thinking
about why.

40:11.007 --> 40:13.844
So sit back, relax.

40:13.878 --> 40:15.980
I'm gonna burn myself.

40:16.012 --> 40:18.715
[dramatic percussive music]

40:18.748 --> 40:25.789
♪ ♪

40:46.277 --> 40:48.579
No, no, no, no,
no, no, no, no, no.

40:48.612 --> 40:51.282
Not yet, creeps.

40:51.315 --> 40:53.184
That was just the roof
of my mouth.

40:53.217 --> 40:54.851
I'd still like
to burn my tongue.

40:54.885 --> 40:57.521
And I wanna tell you,
if that last thing took you

40:57.554 --> 41:00.523
by surprise and up-tightened
you a little bit,

41:00.557 --> 41:02.860
this next thing will probably
make you puke your guts out.

41:02.893 --> 41:05.929
[laughter]

41:20.945 --> 41:23.746
[cheers and applause]

41:27.518 --> 41:30.286
- [groaning]

41:31.454 --> 41:32.422
Okay.
- [smooches]

41:32.456 --> 41:34.157
- Ugh.

41:34.190 --> 41:35.693
Give it up for Penn and Teller

41:35.726 --> 41:37.661
and all of tonight's
performers.

41:37.695 --> 41:38.762
We'll see you next time.

41:38.795 --> 41:40.764
Goodnight from Las Vegas.

41:40.797 --> 41:43.601
[cheers and applause]
